claudeqt-remote for Debian/Ubuntu
==================================

WHAT THIS PACKAGE IS
--------------------
claudeqt-remote is the server-side execution worker for ClaudeQt. It runs as
a stateless daemon that accepts connections from the ClaudeQt desktop GUI
(the "master"), receives per-turn session state over an encrypted JSON-RPC
channel, invokes the Claude Code CLI to produce a response, and streams the
result back. The master holds all persistent session data; this daemon does
not.

INTENDED DEPLOYMENT: CROSS-HOST
-------------------------------
claudeqt-remote is designed to run on a DIFFERENT machine than the one you
run the ClaudeQt desktop app on — a build server, dev container, or
workstation with privileged tools, elevated filesystem access, or hardware
that your laptop doesn't have. Running it on the same box as the master is
supported for development but not recommended: the privilege separation
collapses, and the JSON-RPC roundtrip adds latency without buying isolation.

THE "claudeqt" SYSTEM USER
--------------------------
The package creates a dedicated system user and group, both named "claudeqt",
with home directory /var/lib/claudeqt and login shell /usr/sbin/nologin. The
daemon runs as this user via its systemd unit. The user is unprivileged by
default: no sudo rights, no supplementary group memberships, no write access
outside /var/lib/claudeqt.

GRANTING ELEVATED ACCESS (OPT-IN)
---------------------------------
If your workflow requires the daemon to run commands that need elevated
privileges (e.g., 'systemctl restart nginx', 'docker ps', 'apt list'), you
grant those rights manually.

  Group membership
  ----------------
    sudo usermod -aG docker claudeqt
    sudo usermod -aG www-data claudeqt
    sudo systemctl restart claudeqt-remote

  Sudoers drop-in (narrow whitelist)
  ----------------------------------
  Create /etc/sudoers.d/claudeqt with specific absolute-path entries:

    claudeqt ALL=(root) NOPASSWD: /usr/bin/systemctl restart nginx
    claudeqt ALL=(root) NOPASSWD: /usr/bin/apt-get update
    claudeqt ALL=(root) NOPASSWD: /usr/bin/docker ps

  Validate the file with 'sudo visudo -cf /etc/sudoers.d/claudeqt' before
  saving. NEVER use 'NOPASSWD: ALL' — that defeats the whole purpose of the
  unprivileged daemon account.

WORKSPACE AND FILE ACCESS
-------------------------
When the master sends a project snapshot for a session, the daemon
materializes it under /var/lib/claudeqt/workspace/<session-id>/ and points
Claude at that directory as its working directory. Tool calls (Read, Write,
Edit, Bash) operate inside that scratch tree. When the turn completes, diffs
and outputs stream back to the master, and the scratch tree is reaped.

File snapshots, diffs, and tool output streams are zstd-compressed
end-to-end over the TLS/JSON-RPC transport.

CLAUDE CLI AUTHENTICATION
-------------------------
The Claude Code CLI on the remote box needs its own OAuth login. You have
two options:

  1. Local install (one-time, at NEXT STEPS time after 'apt install'):
         curl -fsSL https://claude.ai/install.sh | sudo -Hu claudeqt bash
         sudo -Hu claudeqt /var/lib/claudeqt/.local/bin/claude /login

     Only the first line is strictly required — /login is optional if you
     plan to use option 2.

  2. Share your desktop session's token at connect time from the ClaudeQt
     GUI. When you connect to this remote for the first time, the desktop
     app queries the daemon's auth state, displays it, and offers to
     forward your local login token over the encrypted connection.

NETWORK ACCESS
--------------
The daemon listens on port 49428 by default (IANA dynamic range, no existing
assignment). All connections use TLS with Ed25519 certificates generated at
install time under /etc/claudeqt/certs/. The port is configurable via
bind_port in /etc/claudeqt/remote.conf.

The shipped systemd unit defaults to IPAddressDeny=any + IPAddressAllow=localhost,
so the daemon is locked to localhost out of the box. To expose it to a LAN
range, create a drop-in file:

    # /etc/systemd/system/claudeqt-remote.service.d/allowlist.conf
    [Service]
    IPAddressAllow=192.168.1.0/24
    IPAddressAllow=10.8.0.0/24

systemd merges IPAddressAllow= additively across the base unit and drop-ins,
so the effective list becomes 'localhost + 192.168.1.0/24 + 10.8.0.0/24'. No
edits to the shipped unit file; drop-ins survive package upgrades.

DOAS ALTERNATIVE
----------------
If you ship opendoas instead of sudo, the install recipe becomes:

    curl -fsSL https://claude.ai/install.sh | \
        doas -u claudeqt env HOME=/var/lib/claudeqt bash

    doas -u claudeqt env HOME=/var/lib/claudeqt \
        /var/lib/claudeqt/.local/bin/claude /login

The explicit 'env HOME=...' is required because doas has no -H flag and
does not rewrite HOME by default.

See also:
  /usr/share/doc/claudeqt-remote/copyright
  https://github.com/ayourk/claudeqt (upstream)
